1 SECTION 1. This Act shall be known and may be cited as the
2 "Mila Microchip Identification Act".
3 SECTION 2. The legislature finds that since January 1,
4 2022, all cat and dog owners in Hawaii have been required to
5 have a microchip implanted in their pet and to register that
6 microchip number and the owner's contact information with a
7 microchip registration company. The legislature further finds
8 that when employees of the state and county agencies responsible
9 for disposing roadkill pick up dead cats and dogs that have been
10 killed on public roadways, they do not routinely scan the
11 deceased animals for microchips or take any other measures to
12 ascertain the animal's owner. As a result, owners of lost cats
13 or dogs are not informed if their pet has been killed by a
14 vehicle.
15 The legislature further finds that the tragic incident
16 involving a dog named Mila, as reported by KITV News on
17 November 8, 2024, highlights a critical gap in existing policies
